---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import cascadeMeme from "../img/cascade-meme.jpeg";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal center" autoplay>
  <h1>Governing the cascade</h1>
  <Image
    p-effect="from above"
    src={cascadeMeme}
    alt="cascade meme"
    class="alter-image-size"
    style="--image-start-size: 8em; border-radius: 0.3em; --fragment-duration: 2.5s;"
  />
  <PNotes>
    <p>This is the architectural heart of the talk — slow down here.</p>
    <p>
      Three at-rules, one idea: stop fighting the cascade, start governing it.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">The cascade is implicit</h2>
  <ul style="">
    <li>
      🥊 <span>Specificity </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">wars</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🚨 <span class="main-sub-gradient">!important</span><span>
        as a band-aid</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🏷️ <span>Naming conventions to </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >fake isolation</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🎯 <span>What we actually want: </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >explicit control</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Everyone has lived these three pains. Get a nod from the room before
      moving on.
    </p>
    <p>
      The last bullet is the thread for the whole section — say it deliberately.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>layer</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>First lever: control WHERE a rule sits in the cascade.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Stratify specificity</h3>
  <ul style="">
    <li>
      📚 <span>Declare the </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >layer order</span
      ><span> once</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🏆 <span>Later layers </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">win</span
      ><span> — regardless of specificity</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧱 <span class="main-sub-gradient">base → components → overrides</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The mental model: priority follows declaration order, not specificity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gotcha to flag verbally: unlayered styles beat every layer. Keep almost
      everything in a layer.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient"
      ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>layer — order is everything</span
    > 📚
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="layers.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-scss">/* declare the order once — this is the whole stuff */
    @layer reset, base, components, overrides;

    @layer base {
        a { color: blue; }
    }

    @layer components {
        section a { color: white; } /* higher specificity… */
    }</code><p-fragment>
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-scss">
    @layer overrides {
        a { color: rebeccapurple; } /* …yet this one wins */
    }</code>
    </p-fragment>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Build the tension: components has a more specific selector, so people
      expect it to win.
    </p>
    <p>
      Reveal the overrides layer — point at it. Order beats specificity. Let it
      land.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>scope</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Second lever: control WHERE in the DOM a rule applies.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Isolation without naming</h3>
  <ul style="">
    <li>
      🎯 <span>Styles apply </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >only inside a subtree</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🚫 <span>No BEM, no </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >invented conventions</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🍩 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Donut scope</span><span>
        — set a lower boundary</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the slide that replaces a thousand .card__title--active class
      names.
    </p>
    <p>
      Land the donut scope bullet last — it's the surprising one. "You can also
      say where the scope stops." Sets up the code slide.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Scoping</span> — naming vs the platform 🎯
  </h5>
  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="tag">
        Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">faked with naming</span>
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="card.scss">
        <code style="font-size: 0.55em" is:raw class="language-scss">
        /* the convention IS the isolation */
        .card {}
        .card__title {}
        .card__title--active {}
        .card__media {}</code>
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Left: we invented a grammar of double-underscores and dashes to fake
      isolation. Everyone recognizes it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Right: the browser scopes by structure, not by name. Naming becomes less
      responsible for isolation.
    </p>
    <p>Then move to the full @scope slide with the boundary example.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient"
      ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>scope — locality by design</span
    > 🎯
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="card.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* applies only inside section — no section__title needed */
    @scope (section) {
        :scope { padding: 1rem; color: green; } /* the scope root itself */
        h2 { color: red; } /* only h2 inside the section */
    }</code>
    <p-fragment>
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* style the section, but stop before its footer */
    @scope (section) to (footer) {
        p {  margin: 0;  color: blue; } /* doesn't leak into footer */
    }</code>
</p-fragment>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>:scope is the scope root itself — explain it in one sentence.</p>
    <p>
      Donut scope (the "to" boundary) is the killer feature for slot-based
      components.
    </p>
    <p>
      If someone asks about overlapping scopes: proximity wins — the closer
      scope root takes precedence. New cascade rule.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>property</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Third lever: control WHAT a variable means and how it inherits.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Typed custom properties</h3>
  <ul style="">
    <li>
      🏷️ <span>Give a variable a real </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >type</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🎬 <span>Suddenly </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">animatable</span
      ><span> gradients, angles</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🛡️ <span>Invalid values </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >fall back</span
      ><span>, don't break</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🧬 <span>Explicit </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">inheritance</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The "animatable" point is the wow moment — a plain --var can't be
      transitioned, a typed one can.
    </p>
    <p>
      "Fall back" is the safety net — invalid values don't silently break the
      layout. Mention it as the boring but important bullet.
    </p>
    <p>
      Explicit inheritance: you opt in, children don't inherit by accident.
      Contrast with plain custom properties.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient"
      ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>property — variables with a
      type</span
    > 🏷️
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="property.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em;" is:raw class="language-scss">
    @property --angle {
        syntax: "&lt;angle&gt;";
        inherits: false;
        initial-value: 0deg;
    }

    [data-glow] {
        background: conic-gradient(from var(--angle), #c850c0, #4158d0);
        transition: --angle 0.4s; /* now this animates */
    }

    [data-glow]:hover {
        --angle: 180deg;
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Walk it top to bottom: syntax = the type, inherits + initial-value =
      controlled propagation.
    </p>
    <p>
      The transition line is the payoff — without @property the browser has no
      idea how to interpolate an angle.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide cascade-recap>
  <h2 class="main-gradient center">Explicit control over how CSS propagates</h2>
  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5em;">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <h4>
        <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>layer</span
        >
      </h4>
      <p>where in the <strong>cascade</strong></p>
    </div>
    <div p-effect="zoom">
      <h4>
        <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>scope</span
        >
      </h4>
      <p>where in the <strong>DOM</strong></p>
    </div>
    <div p-effect="from right">
      <h4>
        <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          ><span style="font-family: Arial;">@</span>property</span
        >
      </h4>
      <p>what a <strong>variable</strong> means</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>This is the slide they should photograph. Hold on it.</p>
    <p>
      Tie the bow: three at-rules, one principle — we decide how styles
      propagate instead of discovering it at runtime.
    </p>
    <p>Transition into section 4 — modern color.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<style lang="scss">
  [cascade-recap] {
    div {
      text-align: center;
      h4 {
        margin-block: 0 0.3em;
        font-size: 1.1em;
      }
      p {
        font-size: 0.6em;
        opacity: 0.85;
        margin: 0;
      }
    }
  }
</style>
